    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hmm okay. but i did notice the soil feels kinda depleted? like i've been growing in the same spot for a few seasons and i feel like something is sucking the life out of the dirt. how do i check if it's actually a nitrogen deficiency and what should i do about the ph levels to fix it?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "To check for nitrogen deficiency, sprinkle a little hydrogen peroxide on the soil near your plant's base; if the leaves turn bright green within an hour, your soil lacks nitrogen. Since you've been growing in the same spot, your soil's pH might be out of balance, making nutrients inaccessible to your plant. To fix this, you can add compost to replenish organic matter and adjust the pH using lime (if too acidic) or sulfur (if too alkaline). Finally, consider rotating your plants to a fresh spot each season to prevent the soil from becoming depleted.",
